{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4ed53a8-854e-437b-9934-549e387fa7a3","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be exe for a tool -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI name users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be executable.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get an API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum configuration. Want me to create or update your `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d194c2cb-9b3f-4409-8ee1-aa817f53b634","outputTokens":489},"id":"a68397d1-1fd5-4a0f-a672-be4cdf4ed38c","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:48:09.937Z","parentId":"68515810-3398-425c-997b-4376db9830ac"}
